** Mason - Chinese, Indian, and Muslim Early Dev
*** Notes
    - Earliest phase of Chinese civilization: Shang dynasty
      - Bronze workers
      - Potter's wheel
      - horse-drawn chariots
      - growing rice
      - weaving silk
      - present ideographic script in an early pictographic form
      - sexigesimal numeral system
	- taken as evidence of Babylonian influence
	- 1000 B.C. the shan Shang dynasty fell to the border Chou peoples
    - Iron, sixth century B.C.
      - 513 B.C.
    - Ch'in dynasty, 221-207 B.C.
      - Notable additions to the Great Wall
    - Han Dynasty
      - 202 B.C. to A.D. 220
      - Imperial university founded in 124 B.C.
      - Notable for its technical innovations
      - orientating effect of a magnet C. 100 B.C.
      - first record of casting iron
    - Invention of paper - Tshai Lun, A.D. 105
    - Mohists (Mo Ti) c. 479-381 B.C.
      - universal love
      - trained themslves in military arts in order to help the weak states oppressed by the strong
    - Han Dynasty beginning
      - Only the Confucians and Taoists were important
    - Confucians
      - Not interested in nature of the universe
      - no natural philosophy until Neo-Confucian movement of Sung times, A.D. 960-1279
      - were associated with official astronomers of the bureaucracy
	- shared their views as to the nature of the universe
      - not interested in chemical and craft problems
	- Left this completely to Taoists
    - Taoism (Daoism)
      - Followers of Lao Tsu
      - lived between sixth and fourth century B.C.
      - suggested that men should abandon civilized society and return to the simple egalitarian communities of ancient times
	- perfect virtue when "men lived in common with birds and beasts, and formed one family with all creatures"
      - Way of nature and way of man
      - cosmic process
      - follow the way of the universe, control human mortality
      - make youth eternal
      - respiration techniques, imitating breathing in embryo
      - men should sunbathe and women expose themselves to the moon
	- yang and yin essences given out by sun and moon
	  - (阴阳)
    - Guess and test
    - Shih Shen c. 350 B.C.
      - Most famous Chinese astronomer
      - Mapped out relative positions of 800 stars
      - knew that eclipses were interference effects between the heavenly bodies and gave rules for the prediction fo eclipses based on expected poitions of the sun and moon
      - 365 and 1/4 days in a year
      - aware of Metonic cycle of 19 years, 236 lunar months
    - Hu Hsi
      - Discovered precession of the equinoxes in A.D. 336
    - Pole star never moved so was the emperor of the sky
    - Three main world systems
      - Ka Thien system
	- held that the skies were a hemispherical vault
	- earth an inverted bowl with linear edges => forms a convex square
	- Heaven is not a regular hemisphere, elevated in the south, depressed in the north
	- like 'an umbrella inclined over a chess board'
	- Sun roating around the hemisphere, visiblee when in the south but not when in the north
	- sun, moon, and planets roate with the heaven, but have proper motions of their own
	- heaven was 80,000 li above the earth three Li equal to one English mile)
	- Disappeared by end of Han times, replaced by Hun Thien "Celestial Sphere" theory
	- Confucians
      - Hun Thien "Celestial Sphere"
	- originated in second century B.C.
	- universe has no shape
	- space is infinite and empty
	- no substance beyond earth and heavenly bodies
	- heavenly bodies not attached
	- moved freely propelled by "hard winds"
	- Taoists
    - Did not conceive heavenly bodies as divine and powerful beings
    - no divine law-giver controlling the universe
    - cosmic process = a web of interrelations between the varied objects of nature, ordered by custom
    - Views on the universe
      - Taoists: all of the elements in the cosmic process are of equal weight (importance)
      - Confucians: not all things are of equal weight, but they are all interrelated and bound by the force of custom
    - Thang
      - Many Thang emperors died from an overdoes of the 'pill of immortality'
      - gunpowder developed
    - firearms appeared before the end of Sung
      - had firearms by A.D. 1237
    - Magnetic compass
      - for land and sea travel
      - rub the needle on a lodestone, hang it up by a thin thread
	- will point south, sometimes north
    - Chinese science at its best: speculation with acute observation
    - Chinese society was not about individualism
      - Thus, no atomism
      - most individualistic person was a Taoist hermit in the wilderness
