** Huff - Science and Civilisation in China
*** Notes
    - It was the lack of metaphysical leap from geocentric to heliocentric universe that prevented the Arabs from making more progress
    - China was more efficient in "applying human natural knowledge to practical human needs." (241)
    - superiority was wholly of a practical and technological nature, not of theoretical understanding
    - Science at its heart is systematic and theoretical knowledge about how the world is and how it works
      - always conjecturing existance of new entities, processes, mechanisms, new worlds
    - /episteme/ as opposed to /techne/
    - inventiveness of Chinese could be seen as a lack of freedom in an intellectual sense, not delving into the metaphysical realm
    - Chinese excelled in empirical observations rather
    - lagged behind in much everything else
    - Geometry as systematic deductive system of proofs and demonstrations were virtually nonexistent in China, along with trigonometry
    - Chinese did not realize that the geographic location changed astronomical calculations until 1447
      - Arab astronomers knew of the changes in location and calculated time accordingly
    - Chinese astronomers didn't accept other mathematical influence from Islam and Persia
      - more algebra-based point-estimation system rather than geometrical analysis
    - Chinese were greatly hampered by the lack of the Greek deductive geometry
      - Arabs inherited this geometry
    - "protest against asking why modern science did not emerge in China is ill-considered" meaning?
    - To disregard such inquiries as to why one social group or another, one society or civilization or another, did not follow a particular line, etc, leading to higher levels of scientific achievement and eceonomic performance, is little more than moral censure
      - harsh criticism
    - by 1644, Chinese mathematics and astronomy had merged with Europe
      - end of Ming dynasty
    - China's long history of herbal medicine is now combined with the one universal science of pharmaceuticals
    - "Chinese leaders have recognized that modern science and technology contain elements of indispensable truth well worth having"
    - Chinese education focused more on moral uprightness and historical figures rather than rudimentary things like mathematics and mundane scientific pursuits per se
    - 
*** Cues
    - Chinese had a hard time accepting Greek and Arab mathematics and concepts
    - Thought less about metaphysical aspect of everything
    - "protest against asking why modern science did not emerge in China is ill-considered" meaning?
