** W12D1
*** Notes
    - Think about the convtroversy, the sources, the philosophy
    - *Presentation by Divya Kartik*
    - Overview
      - did not have theoretical geometry
      - theory of the universe wasn't based upon quantitative observations
      - experimental observations to make empirical rules
      - Shang Dynasty (1500 BCE - 1000 BCE)
	- On the yellow river
	- bronze work, pottery, and silk
	- ideographic script in an early pictographic form
	- sexagesimal number system
      - Han Dynasty (202 BCE - 220 CE)
	- Founded the imperial university in 234 BCE
	- One of the biggest contributions was writing - originally on bamboo slips, then paper
	- noted for technical innovations
	  - espcially *paper* - ascribed to Cai Lun
	  - casting of iron etc.
    - Writing
      - Pictographic language
      - often uses phonetic and semantic indicators
      - non-inflectional language - words don't change with number, gender, tense or mood
      - relationships are indicated by word order or auxiliary words like 了
      - Radicals
	- semantic indicators
    - Math
      - earliest CHinese mathematical work is /Arithmetic in Nine Sections/
	- areas of triangles, trapeziums and circles
	- volumes of figures
	- proportions, precentages and partnerships
	- linear simultaneous equations
	- algebraic methods of solving trigonometrical problems
	- guess and test
    - Schools of Philosophy
      - Divided on the question of how to stop wars between states
      - Legalist
	- chaos can only be ordered by positive law
      - Mohist and Logician
	- Mohists were followers of Mo Ti
	- Believed in a doctrine of universal love but weren't pacifists
	- investigated problems in physics
	  - optics
	  - mechanics
	  - scientific method
    - Confucianism
      - Little or no natural philosophy until 960 CE
      - weren't interested in chemicals or craft
      - pursued the unity of the individual self and the God of Heaven
      - achieve "perfection" by becoming one with the rhythms of the universe
      - "do not do to others as you would not wish done to yourself"
      - 水 symbol of confucianism
    - Taoism
      - Men should abandon civilized society and return to simple commmunities of ancient times - equal to all other creatures
      - do not believe in a single creator, but rather put faith in the natural order of the universe
      - does not emphasise rigid rituals and social order (unlike Confucianism)
    - Yin and Yang
      - believed in by all schools - rooted in Taoism
      - yin - passive, dark, female force
      - yang - active, light, male force
      - interaction between the two produced the five elements of fire, water, wood, metal, and earth
      |-----------------+----------+---------|
      | Phenomenon      | Yin      | Yang    |
      |-----------------+----------+---------|
      | Celstial Bodies | moon     | sun     |
      | genders         | female   | male    |
      | location        | inside   | outside |
      | temperature     | cold     | hot     |
      | direction       | down     | up      |
      | humidity        | wet/damp | dry     |
      |-----------------+----------+---------|
    - Medicine
      - Used dietetic techniques to prolong life and cure sicknesses
      - classified all sicknesses with either yin or yang character
      - treated based upon the yin and yang characteristics of food
      - anatomy/physiology was based off the analogies of man to the universe - five phases theory
	- flow of qi through the body through 12 major meridians
    - Alchemy
      - Started by Taoists
	- concerned with quest for pill of immortality rather than transmutation of gold - cinnabar was more important
      - popularity dropped after a whlie (during second warring states due to introduction of Buddhism)
      - more, missed
    - Tech Advances
      - under Tang dynasty
	- high perfection of porcelain manufacture
	- invention of wheelbarrow
	- tread-mill operated paddle boats ith water-tight bulkheads and a stern-post rudder
	- block printing
	- gunpowder - mmixture of saltpeter and sulfur
      - under the Sung dynasty
	- use of magnetic compass for land and sea travel
    - Astronomy
      - pole star and circumpolar stars were most important as the pole star neve rmoved
      - mainly concerned with developing a calendar
      - calculations were almost entirely algebraic
      - three main world systems: Ka Tian, Hun Tian, Xuan Ye
      - Taoist vs Confucian view
      - astrology and divination
    - Shortcomings
      - Chinese advancement was based on practical technological nature, NOT on theoretical understanding
      - sciences but no conception for the overarching sum of them all
      - lagged behind both west and arabs
      - geometry, system of proofs and demonstrations, not existent in China
      - difference in cultural outlook
    - Things to say in class
      - The difference in writing system, how that affected their development
