** W12D2
*** Notes
    - Arabic an Islamic Developments - Noah Giles
    - Setting the scene for Islamic Science
      - Alexander the Great conquered Asia and North Africa (334-323 BC) and left behind Hellenistic ideas
      - Religion also playe da huge part in promoting not only learning, but also the exchanging of ideas especially in western Asia (Manicheism, Zoroastrianism, and Christianity were the big three religions in the region)
    - Arabia is in the middle of everywhere, centralized portion of the world
    - Chrisetians bring Greek ideas to Persia
      - Missionaries established monasteries as well as churches and persecuted Nestorian Christians coming from the byzantine Empire
    - Nestorian Christian Influence cont.
      - Translated it into Aramaic and Arabic
      - Not just about oral transmittion but also writing it down
      - Gondeshapur, a medicine city
	- religions scholars with ideas in medicine were integraded into Abbasid courts as physicians
    - Enter Islam
      - Prophet Muhammad was born in 570 A.D and started spreading Islam in the Arabian Peninsula with his successors eventually uniting the whole peninsula and expanding north into Persia and Byzantium
      - Didn't just expand the empire with religion, was a normal guy before this
      - Qur'an largely defined all aspects of Islamic life and was the method and means of education
    - Beginning of Islamic Hellenisation
      - Umayyads (from 641 to ~750 A.D.) set up in Damascus and used Syrians and Persians as secretaries
      - In 750 
    - Benefits of Empire
      - Abbasids united the whole Western Asia / Middle Eastern region and a large part of Africa under one empire which made exchanging of ideas across the region much easier
      - Further, paper from China made recording, translating, and sharing knowledge much more attainable
      - Having become a minority, the Abbasids wanted to make the transition of rule go smoothly so they emulated Persian rulers in terms of scientific stance
    - Islamic Science
      - based around building off of and refining Greek ideas
      - Key method of transmitting and recording knowledge was through books
      - Al-Kwarizmi analysed Indian math and Euclidian geometry to create a refind number system and Algebra. Trigonometry was an extension of Ptolemy's Almagest and the Indian Siddhanta
      - All of these advanced astronomy and in turn were advanced by astronomy
    - Peer Review and Continued Extrapolation
      - Caliph Al-Ma'mun (786-833 A.D.)
    - Islamic Science
      - Optics
    - Optics
      - Rainbows
	- Ibn Sina, relfection of solar light by individual droplets of moisture that make up a cloud
	- Kamal al-Din
	  - First rainbow was made from reflection and refraction, second rainbow made through two internal reflections
    - Medicine
      - Pre-Islamic medicine, prophetic medicine, bloodletting etc
      - Actual hospitals (institutions) oculists, bonesetters, and surgeons; starting to spring up in Baghdad
	- 800 A.D.
    - Qur'an goes against atomism
      - led to a separation of religion and science?
    - Organized body of medical work
    - /Cannon of Medicine/ by Ibn Sina
      - five headings
	1) generalities
	2) herbal and non herbal remidies
	3) diseases head to toe
	4) dieases not specific to one part of the body
	5) compound drugs
      - Ib al-Nafis (1213-1288 AD) discovered pulmonary transit of blood
    - Larger Significance
      - The Islamic world developed dedicated institutions, made science more accessible through translation, and expanded the role of specialists
      - Cultural mixing combined with the rise of patrons allowed for different ideas to exist on thesame point and further encouraged the exchange / refinement of those ideas
      - The Islamic world gathered and organized seperate scientific thought into one uniform whole, which allowed for a more comprehensive in depth study of the material
