   1. What were some of the key innovations in Europe in this time?
   2. What was 'special' about Europe in developing science?
** Huff - What Happened in Europe - Chinese Overview
*** Notes
    - "nothing in Chinese thought equivalent to
      - Greek philosophy as expressed by Aristotle"
      - Christian theology
      - /corpus juris civilis/
    - 12th and 13th centuries that universities arose in Europe
      - neutral zones of intellectual autonomy
      - allowed philosophers to pursuie their agendas free from the dictates of the central state and the religious authorities
    - New intellectual agenda was thoroughly naturalistic
      - scientific core of readings and lectures
      - core of evolutionary course of study
    - questions of existance, vacuums
    - No established zones for public forums in China
    - no legally autonomous universities
    - Freedom of action, of contract, and of self-governance were all absent in China
    - Travel was more open and encouraged in the Middle East and Europe
    - Medical professionals could never gain positions of power in China
*** Summary
    - China was generally impeded by the lack of intellectual freedom and neutral spaces where thoughts could be debated openly
