* Week 14
** Lindberg - Ch.12 Physics of Sublunar Region
*** Notes
** Revival of Learning in the West
*** Notes
    - Outline
      - Middle ages overview
      - Dissemination
      - Schools and Approach
	- Growth of universities
	- Curriculum and (impressive) autonomy
      - Philosophy I
      - Philosophy II
      - Institutionalised
    - Middle Ages
      - Idea of Middle Ages from 14th-15th C Italian Humanists, covering *roughly* 500-1450 [500-1000 early, 1000-1200 high, 1200-1450 late]
      - Early M.A. was de-urbanised and Monasteries dominant educational force, focusing on religion, though some earlier work survived (Aristotle e.g.)
	- Boethius (applied Airstotelian logic to theology)
	- Isidore of Seville (used philosophical tradition as comparison for religion)
	- Gregory of Tours
	- Gregory the Great (phil. underpinnings)
	- Bede
    - Dissemination in Europe
      - Charlemagne 8th C burst of learning as empire grew and centralised.
	- Alcuin brought liberal arts and astronomy, raised education of clergy with mandate for education
      - John Scotus Eriugena (c860) trans. Greek texts and enhanced Neoplatonism
      - Gerbert (c.970s-1000), later Pope, travelled widely and disseminated learning, particualrly mathematical
      - Translation (boomed in early 12th C) developed through individuals and recoquests. Gerard of Cremona translated the /Almagest/ (c1140s) and huge numbers of others in all disciplines
    - Islamic World
      - [[file:./Week 14/islamicworldmap_214258.png]]
    - Islamic Advance
      - 'the scholar's ink is holier than the martyr's blood'
      - By the end of the 8th C.e., Islam had already assimilated most of the extant great works from Greece, AIran, and India. This assimilation was made possible through an extraordinary movement of translation, which has possibly no equivalent in history
      - Immediately following, In the 8th trhough the 10th centuries, early scientists like Al-Haytham, Jabir ibn Hayyan (Geber) and Abu Bakr al-Razi advanced a set of techniques, tools, and principles for controlled and precise experimentation--the proto scientific method!
      - Any study that improved the tasks of daily life was encouraged
	- medical knowledge
	- ways of measuring and calulating for maps
	  - buildings
	- tools for agriculture
	- general craft industries (papermaking)
	- relied on their own experiments more than on authorities
	- alchemical studies formed an important part of other industries such as metal-working, ceramics, pharmacy, and dyeing
      - Input, flood of texts
      - Withdrawal from the sciences (Al-Ghazali), religious division, and conquests heralded the end of this 'golden period' in the 13th C
	- Al-Ghazali
	  - reason leads to hell
	  - anything that quibbled with metaphysical ideas was frowned upon
    - Schools, Universities, and Approach
      - 11th and 12th C Schools, from
	1) stronger, ordering monarchies
	2) secure borders
	3) growing moey economy and trade
	4) technological improvements, particularly as concerns food production
	5) population explosion and re-urbanisation that concentrated money and interest in education
      - Clergy schools open to all for a fee and broke off (in curriculum and geography) as needed for the clientele (medicine, law, logic, maths). Regional foci--France attached to cathedrials but broad; Italy law and medicine; Britain theology and logic
      - Managerial revolution--reason can reform/address all
      - Reason applied to 'support and defend' religion. Anselm (c.1080s) ontological proof of God. Peter Abelard (c1120s) continued reason's challenge to dogma
      - Advanced from simply teh Trivium ("the three roads") of grammar, rhetoric and logic, to the Quadrivium ("the four roads") of arithmetic, geometry, music, and astronomy/cosmology
      - Centres grew in cities and attracted masters and pupils, which eventually called for organisation, securing rights, and protections akin to the merchant guild structure
	- Bizarrily democratic institution
    - "Philosophy - the 'invited guest' stays"
      - Emphasised philosophy, law, morality, logic, and Aristotle! in a fairly consistent curriculum with great freedom of study
      - Natural Philosophy 12th C - Plato's *\ /\Timaeus\/ \* key (until Aristotle in the 13thc), which advanced on ordered, law-bound divine cosmology. Needed to fit with bible -> Thierry of Chartres (c1150s) restricted divine intervention to first moment of creation. After that it is all natural causes
      - William of Conches (c1150s) followed this tradition and took it to English royalty: exhaust natural explanation before considering miracles. The complexity of natural processes only further supports divine power
      - Rise of humanism, studying humans and their powers in their own right. Macrocosm and microcosm mirror. Numerology and astrology also grew but as a distant side note.
    - Philosophy II
      - The pursuit of truth, became the *motto* of European universities and they claimed freedom on that ground. They were /mini democracies/ founded upon and justified by their merit and aims with legal protections and autonomy unlike any other such body
      - Coupled with the historical particularly of separation of church and state rule, the Christian conception of an absolute God, a god with unlimited powers enabled the broader and freer contemplation of alternatives, the nature of the universe, the mechanisms that made it work, etc.
    - Institutionalised
      - The universities "sprang into existence ...  without express authorization of king, pope, prince, or prelate. They were spontaneous products of that instinct of association which swept like a great wave over the towns of Europe in the eleventh and twelfth centuries" (H. Rashdall, 1936)
      - Lrgely through monumental efforts at translation and dissemination, by 1200 Europe had as astonishing collection of scientific texts that formed the heart of the nascent universities: Euclid's /Elements/, Ptolemy's /Almagest/, Ibn al-Haythem's /Optics/, the algebra of al-Khwarizmi, ritings of Glaen and Hippocrates, Ibs Sina's /Canon of Medicine/, and many works by Aristotle, including /Physics, On the Heavens, On Generation and Corruption, On the Soul, Metorology, The Small Works of Natural Things, The History of Animals, The Parts of Animals, and The Generation of Animals.../
      - Europeans had no issue with combining the craft of scholarly traditions, and used both methods in their endless conquests
*** Questions
    - 
*** Summary
    - Middle ages overview
    - Dissemination
    - Schools and Approach
      - Growth of universities
      - Curriculum and (impressive) autonomy
    - Philosophy I
    - Philosophy II
    - Institutionalised
** W14D1
*** Notes
    + *Dylan Chalcraft Presentation*
    + *Medieval (Meta)Physics and the Rise of Western Universities*
    + Context
      - Western Roman Empire falls, beginning of the so called "dark ages."
      - Christanity grows spreads and becomes the dominant religion in Europe
	- Source of identity
	- Sort of gives a moral compass
      - War and conflict inhibit widespread advances in philosophy outside of the church
      - Renaissance marks the end of the middle ages
    + Medieval (Meta)Physics
      - Heavily influenced by Aristotle's work, using Aristotle as a starting point
      - There is a resurgence of the explorations of Forms and Natures
      - Medieval Philosophers defined two types of form, Substantial and Accidental forms
    + Matter and Form
      - Ibn Sina (980-1037) and Ibn Rushd (1126-98) worked with the links between matter and form
      - They thought that the creation of the elements was not the simple two step process described by Aristotle. A third step was necessary
      - Corporeal Form, the third form, which must be applied to the matter to create a three dimensional body, which is then ready to receive its elemental form
    + Combinations
      - Central to the four elements theory is that all things are constituted of the four elements
      - Questioning of how these mixtures are aligned raise the possibility of prime movers, celestial forces, or even God creating these combinations that create new Substantial Forms
      - Other questions that were considered was the problem of how to explain the reemergence of elements after the destruction of the Substantial Form
      - Alchemy also continued to be explored, which was mainly focused on chemically changing base metals into precious metals
    + Europ's Educational Revival
      - Imperial growht allowed for more learning and study, specifically in the Charlemagne's church "approved" Holy Roman empire
      - Clergy run schools teach later generations
      - Neo-Platonism grows in popularity during the spread of classical knowledge, along with the translation of works into different languages
    + Islamic Unity
      - Islam's extent and infrastructure allowed for leanring on a much more efficient and larger scale than in Europe at the time
      - Big cities contain libraries and allow access to important classical works, along with bookmaking to document contemporary advances
      - Scientists as we know them today begin to emerge, exploring to how to experiment precisely
      - Invation (Crusades and Mongols, hurray) and Islamic power concerns lead to science and philosophy to fall out of favor
    + Rise of Universities
      - Foundation of Schools due to secure governments in growing cities in the 11th century
      - Specialization in fields is aided by education
      - Clergy schools are now open to all for tuition
    + Philosophy
      - Philosophy is established though medieval universities as the inital overarching concept, and all other subjects break off from it
    + Questions
      - Should the Middle Ages be referred to as a dark age?
      - Was the Islamic Caliphate's concern about scientific questioning called for?
      - In a world without the great universities, would society still be able to function at our level of education and intellectual thought?
    + *PRESENTATION END*
    + Temaeus
      - ordered cosmology
